DOC.TEXT:
   Skies were clear across the country early today, except for some
fog in the Northeast.
   Dry Pacific air was expected to end a record warm spell in the
East. Highs were expected to reach the 60s and 70s, and
temperatures could drop into the 40s tonight.
   Cities setting record highs for the date Sunday included
Atlantic City, N.J., 84 degrees; Bridgeport, Conn., 80, and
Charleston, S.C., 88.
   Sunshine was the forecast for most the country today, with only
Maine, Florida and the Pacific Northwest looking for rain. A cold
front was expected to hold over the northern part of the country,
keeping temperatures in the 40s and 50s.
   Highs were expected to reach the 60s in the Midwest, the 80s in
the South and the 90s in the Southwest.
   The high temperature for the nation Sunday was 98 degrees at
Borrego Springs, Calif.
   Other reports at 5 a.m. EDT:
